liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: As of October 30 more than 1.4 million people in Gaza were "internally displaced", according to the UN's latest updates. "This figure includes nearly 672,00 people staying in 150 UNRWA facilities, 121,750 sheltering in hospitals, churches, and other public buildings, and nearly 83,000 in 72 non-UNRWA schools," the organisations latest humanitarian update says. "In addition, the Ministry of Social Development estimates that some 700,000 internally displaced persons (IDPs) are residing with host families." It adds giving assistance to around 300,000 displaced people in 100 centres is "increasingly challenging" because of the intensity of airstrikes and hostility. "The average number of IDPs per shelter in UNRWA facilities has reached almost four times their intended capacity. "The Khan Younis Training Centre is currently the most crowded shelter, hosting 22,100 IDPs, more than 10 times its capacity. "Over 15 per cent of the IDPs are estimated to have disabilities, yet most shelters are not adequately equipped for their needs. "Shelters lack the required medical mattresses and beds, causing ulcers and other medical issues that cannot be treated in unsterilised conditions."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Reserve Bank has warned that there could be "a regime shift characterized by structurally higher interest rate volatility" in the years ahead. In a speech on emerging threats to financial stability on Tuesday, RBA assistant governor Brad Jones said supply shocks, a higher and more volatile bond term premium and reduced smoothing from price-insensitive buyers were the potential contributing factors to a structurally higher interest rate volatility, despite that much of the past two decades saw long-term interest rate volatility either decline or languish at unusually subdued levels. He said a period of structurally higher interest rate volatility would present several challenges to financial system stability. "Banks of all sizes will have to manage overall duration risk more intently," Mr Jones said. "Over much of the past few decades, growth in incomes consistently exceeded the level of interest rates. This dampened credit risks for lenders. But debt servicing among borrowers with high debt levels will be more challenging â and credit risks will increase as a result â in an environment where interest rates periodically exceed the growth in incomes. "The post-GFC era of exceptionally low interest rate volatility gave rise to a new generation of investment business models and strategies. "It remains to be seen how market functioning could be affected in a regime of higher inflation and interest rate volatility, including where open-end fixed-income funds encounter liquidity stress, margining is more tightly enforced than in the past, and broker-dealers are unable or unwilling to supply liquidity."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Superannuation fund AustralianSuper said on Tuesday it plans to vote against a Brookfield-led consortium's $US9.78 billion takeover offer for Origin Energy, casting doubt on the future of the bid. AustralianSuper owns a 13.68 per cent stake in Origin Energy and said the offer was "substantially below" its estimate of long-term value for Australia's biggest energy retailer. Origin shares were down 0.9 per cent in early trade on Tuesday at $9.10 each, which was above the $8.81 offer price. The deal requires 75 per cent support from the votes cast at a shareholder meeting, meaning AustralianSuper's holding could be enough to scupper the bid if not all shareholders vote. Brookfield-consortium's offer price of $8.81 per share has been deemed fair by an independent expert's report, however, it outlined a "roll forward" calculation that says Origin's shares could be worth an additional 40 Australian cents by the time a potential takeover is due to occur. The Brookfield-led consortium has given no indications publicly it is considering upping the value of its bid. "No doubt the negotiations between the bidders and key shareholders like AustralianSuper are ongoing," said Max Vickerson, analyst at stockbroker Morgans. "Given that AusSuper felt the need to go public it suggests that maybe they're not that close to a deal. It's hard to say definitively that the takeover won't happen as someone could still blink before the vote but itâs not a good sign." Origin shares have been trading above the offer price since the deal got an approval from the country's competition regulator on October 10. Origin shares closed at $9.17 on Monday, 4.1 per cent above the offer price. AustralianSuper, which engaged consultancy firm Frontier Economics to review the independent expert's report, said the firm was also of the opinion that the assumptions used to come at a business valuation were "unrealistically low". "The current offer from the Brookfield and EIG-backed consortium remains substantially below our estimate of Origin's long-term value," the firm said. Brookfield and EIG's MidOcean Energy did not immediately respond to a Reuters request for comment. Reuters
